  "prompt": "Why is The Sandman called 'sandman'?",
  "response": "The term \"sandman\" has its origins in folklore and mythology, where it refers to a mythical being who is said to sprinkle sand in the eyes of children to help them fall asleep, leading to dreams. The idea is that the sand makes their eyes heavy and induces sleepiness.\n\nIn the context of Neil Gaiman's graphic novel series \"The Sandman,\" the title character, Dream, also known as Morpheus, is the personification of dreams. He governs the realm of dreams and is responsible for creating and shaping the dreams that people experience. His association with the concept of the sandman derives from this role as a figure who influences sleep and dreams, blending the folklore with a rich narrative that explores various themes related to dreams, reality, and the human experience. \n\nOverall, the name \"sandman\" encapsulates the character's function as both a bringer of dreams and a powerful, enigmatic figure within the world Gaiman created.",
